vectorData.altText: 10. The _______________ nerve is associated with cutaneous sensation over the medial hand, as indicated by the letter A.
That's right! The ulnar nerve is responsible for cutaneous sensation over the medial hand.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

Recall that the ulnar nerve passes through the anterior compartment of the forearm like the filling in a sandwich     , between the flexor carpi ulnaris and the medial (“ulnar”) half of flexor digitorum profundus.  
The flexor carpi ulnaris contributes to flexion and adduction of the wrist. The “ulnar” half of flexor digitorum profundus flexes the DIP joints of digits 4 and 5. Recall that weakness in flexion of the DIP joints of digits 4 and 5 is suggestive of an ulnar nerve at or above the medial epicondyle. 
As you will learn in exercise 17.2, the ulnar nerve innervates most of the intrinsic muscles of the hand and is sensory over the medial portion of the hand.
The ulnar nerve does not pass through the carpal tunnel. The ulnar nerve is spared in carpal tunnel syndrome.
